==English==
===Definition===
Chew the scenery is a phrase often cited to describe the performance of an [[actor]] to be [[over the top]], [[melodramatic]], or [[flamboyant]]. Often associated with on-screen [[villain]]s, the phrase may be intended as a compliment or as an [[insult]] depending on the context of the scene. Less often, it can be used outside of the stage to refer to anyone who overacts.

===History===
Its earliest reference is listed in the ''Random House Historical Dictionary of American Slang'' as being used by [[Mary Hallock Foote]] in ''Coeur D'Alene'' in [[1894]].[http://www.randomhouse.com/wotd/index.pperl?date=20001024]

